def: The upper rigging, spars, etc., of a ship. [Written also tophamper.]All the ships of the fleet . . . were so encumbered with tophamper,so overweighted in proportion to their draught of water, that theycould bear but little canvas, even with smooth seas and light andfavorable winds. Motley.
That transports; fig., ravishing.Your transporting chords ring out. Keble.
To shine; to emit rays of light. [Obs.] Ure.
In two; in twain; asunder. [Obs.] Chaucer.

Anything which serves to compress; as:(a) (Anat.) A muscle that compresses certain parts.(b) (Surg.) An instrument for compressing an artery (esp., thefemoral artery) or other part.(c) An apparatus for confining or flattening between glass plates anobject to be examined with the microscope; -- called alsocompressorium.(d) (Mach.) A machine for compressing gases; especially, an aircompressor.
An acceptance of a bill by a third person after protest fornonacceptance by the drawee. Burrill.
A state of restlessness and agitation, often with generalindisposition and a distressing sense of oppression at theepigastrium. Dunglison.
